	url = {http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0079661108001468},
	doi = {10.1016/j.pocean.2008.08.001},
	abstract = {In the modern ocean, oxygen minimum zones ({OMZs}) are potential traces of a primitive ocean in which Archean bacteria lived and reduced chemical anomalies occurred. But {OMZs} are also keys to understanding the present unbalanced nitrogen cycle and the oceans’ role on atmospheric greenhouse control. {OMZs} are the main areas of nitrogen loss (as N2, N2O) to the atmosphere through denitriﬁcation and anammox, and could even indirectly mitigate the oceanic biological sequestration of {CO}2. It was recently hypothesized that {OMZs} are going to spread in the coming decades as a consequence of global climate change. Despite an important {OMZ} role for the origin of marine life and for the biogeochemical cycles of carbon and nitrogen, there are some key questions on the structure of {OMZs} at a global scale. There is no agreement concerning the threshold in oxygen that deﬁnes an {OMZ}, and the extent of an {OMZ} is often evaluated by denitriﬁcation criteria which, at the same time, are O2-dependent.},
